      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        What Is Polling Rate?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Polling rate meaning</strong>: polling rate is the frequency at which an input device reports its current position or state to the computer, measured in Hertz (Hz). A mouse with a <strong>polling rate</strong> of 1000Hz sends its coordinates to the PC 1000 times every second — once every 1 millisecond. A 125Hz mouse reports only 8 times per second, resulting in an 8ms interval between updates. The higher the polling rate, the more frequently the OS receives fresh position data, which translates directly into lower input latency and smoother cursor movement.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Understanding <strong>what polling rate does on a mouse</strong> is important for any gamer or power user. It does not change the sensor's DPI or the physical click latency — it only controls how often position data is transmitted over USB or wirelessly. Going from 125Hz to 1000Hz cuts report interval from 8ms to 1ms, a meaningful improvement in fast-paced competitive titles like Valorant, CS2, or Apex Legends.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Run a Mouse Polling Rate Test Online
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Running an <strong>online mouse polling rate test</strong> with this tool takes under 15 seconds. Here is the step-by-step process:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 flex flex-col gap-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <li>Select a test duration (5s, 10s, 15s, 30s, 60s, or Free mode) using the duration buttons on the left panel.</li>
        <li>Click <strong>Start Capture</strong> to begin recording pointer events.</li>
        <li>Move your mouse in fast, steady circular motions inside the test box. Speed matters — slow movements will not saturate the report rate and will return lower readings.</li>
        <li>Once the timer ends (or you click Stop), the tool saves your result to the session history with Hz, median delay, and consistency score.</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        The tool uses <code>PointerEvent.getCoalescedEvents()</code> on Chromium-based browsers (Chrome, Edge, Opera) to retrieve the fine-grained OS-level events that occur between animation frames. This is the only browser-based method that can accurately capture polling rates above the monitor refresh rate, making it suitable for testing <strong>8K polling rate mice</strong> and other high-frequency gaming peripherals.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Polling Rate Test Speed: How to Read Your Results
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        The <strong>polling rate test speed</strong> readout shows several statistics to help you interpret your results accurately:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 flex flex-col gap-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <li><strong>Live Hz</strong> — the smoothed, real-time polling rate estimate based on recent intervals.</li>
        <li><strong>Median Delay</strong> — the median time between consecutive pointer reports. Use this to compare against the expected interval for your mouse's rated polling rate (e.g., 1.0ms for 1000Hz).</li>
        <li><strong>Consistency %</strong> — the percentage of intervals within 15% of the median. A value above 85% indicates a stable, well-functioning report rate with minimal jitter.</li>
        <li><strong>Min / Max Delay</strong> — the fastest and slowest captured intervals, helping diagnose USB scheduling spikes or driver issues.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        Polling Rate Test for Controller & Keyboard
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        While this tool is primarily a <strong>mouse polling rate test online</strong>, it can also give insights into other input devices. For a <strong>polling rate test controller</strong>, wired USB gamepads typically report at 125Hz (8ms). Wireless controllers often have additional radio latency on top of the polling interval. For a <strong>keyboard polling rate test online</strong>, keep in mind that browsers throttle keyboard events independently of pointer events, so results are less precise. Dedicated firmware tools or keyboard software (QMK, Via, manufacturer apps) provide more reliable keyboard polling rate measurements.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        How to Change Mouse Polling Rate
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        If your <strong>polling rate test</strong> result is lower than expected, you can <strong>change your mouse polling rate</strong> through your mouse's companion software. Most major gaming mouse brands offer polling rate settings in their apps:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 flex flex-col gap-1.5 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <li><strong>Logitech</strong> — Logitech G HUB (under Sensitivity or Performance)</li>
        <li><strong>Razer</strong> — Razer Synapse (under Performance → Polling Rate)</li>
        <li><strong>SteelSeries</strong> — SteelSeries GG (under Settings → Polling Rate)</li>
        <li><strong>Corsair</strong> — Corsair iCUE (under Device Settings)</li>
        <li><strong>ASUS</strong> — Armoury Crate (under Mouse Settings)</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        Common options are 125Hz, 250Hz, 500Hz, and 1000Hz. Newer gaming mice with <strong>8K polling rate</strong> support (like the Razer DeathAdder V3 HyperSpeed or Logitech G Pro X Superlight 2) may offer 2000Hz, 4000Hz, or 8000Hz modes. After changing the setting, run this <strong>polling rate checker</strong> again to confirm the new rate is active.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-display font-semibold text-lg text-primary mt-2">
        What Polling Rate Should You Use?
      </h3>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
        For the vast majority of users, <strong>1000Hz is the best polling rate</strong>. It delivers 1ms report intervals with negligible CPU overhead on any modern PC. For competitive esports players who want the absolute lowest input latency, 2000Hz or 4000Hz can provide a marginal edge, provided the system can handle the increased interrupt load. Ultra-high polling rates like 8000Hz are primarily used by professional players and enthusiasts who have optimized their entire hardware stack for minimum latency. For casual and office use, 500Hz is more than adequate. Use this <strong>online mouse polling rate test</strong> to verify whatever setting you choose is working correctly.
